WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Not just how they felt about the training, but also the teacher,

2
00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:05.560
how the staff go away from changes.

3
00:00:05.560 --> 00:00:08.519
So we're looking really hard at how to get a better impact for this,

4
00:00:08.519 --> 00:00:11.519
which would be good for funders, providers and learners.

5
00:00:11.519 --> 00:00:14.519
That tool's rolling out now.

6
00:00:14.519 --> 00:00:17.760
Fourth, the review of the retirement villagers' actors

7
00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:19.240
proceed well.

8
00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:22.160
Legislative drafting has commenced with the bill

9
00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:24.560
intended to be introduced mid-year.

10
00:00:24.560 --> 00:00:28.000
This is the culmination of work we've led since 2020,

11
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.079
working with Housing and Urban Development

12
00:00:31.079 --> 00:00:35.000
to rebalance consumer rights with operator rights.

13
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.000
And fifth, KiwiSaver, recommendation to action.

14
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.840
One of the highlights of the year was the government adoption

15
00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:44.079
of our recommendation to lift KiwiSaver default contributions

16
00:00:44.079 --> 00:00:47.840
from 3% to 4%, and to extend employer and government

17
00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:51.760
contributions to 16 and 17-year-olds.

18
00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:54.280
We calculated that KiwiSaver will now

19
00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:58.679
last 30% longer for median earners,

20
00:00:58.679 --> 00:01:02.840
which is a transformational outcome for many future retirees.

21
00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:04.439
Within two days of the announcement,

22
00:01:04.439 --> 00:01:08.680
there's a 2,500% increase in active users

23
00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:11.280
of the sorted KiwiSaver calculator, which

24
00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:14.000
tells you something about the appetite-trusted,

25
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.960
independent information.

26
00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:21.000
So the breadth of impact of our work across government

27
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.799
and the sector were the very small team.

28
00:01:23.799 --> 00:01:25.759
But the message I must want to leave with you

29
00:01:25.759 --> 00:01:30.560
finally is that a holistic long-term view of the retirement

30
00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:33.399
income system is essential.

31
00:01:33.399 --> 00:01:35.799
Tinkering with settings simply weakens

32
00:01:35.799 --> 00:01:37.920
the structure of the system.

33
00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:42.400
The latest is allowing access to KiwiSaver for farm ownership.

34
00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:44.239
A farm is a business.

35
00:01:44.239 --> 00:01:47.359
This is poor policy and weakens the fundamental purpose

36
00:01:47.359 --> 00:01:50.479
of KiwiSaver being a retirement scheme,

37
00:01:50.479 --> 00:01:53.359
not a general savings or business scheme.

38
00:01:53.359 --> 00:01:56.519
KiwiSaver is, of course, voluntary.

39
00:01:56.519 --> 00:02:00.400
Another tinker earlier allowed total remuneration,

40
00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:02.959
where the employee is actually paying

41
00:02:02.959 --> 00:02:05.920
both their contribution and the employers.

42
00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:08.879
This was not in the original KiwiSaver scheme,

43
00:02:08.879 --> 00:02:13.639
was permitted by a law changed by a national government in 2008.

44
00:02:13.639 --> 00:02:16.599
No subsequent government has repealed it.

45
00:02:16.599 --> 00:02:19.680
It means people have less take-home pay,

46
00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:23.079
and employers are not doing their bit.

47
00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:26.040
Short-term thinking with the retirement income system

48
00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:31.040
is a real threat to the well-being of future older New Zealanders.

49
00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:33.800
That's you.

50
00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:37.240
We delivered our substantial 2025 review

51
00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:40.280
of retirement income policies in December.

52
00:02:40.280 --> 00:02:44.439
Its main message is that system change will happen.

53
00:02:44.439 --> 00:02:46.960
And a cross-party approach is the best way

54
00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:50.080
to develop a principled 10-year plan

55
00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:54.960
to consider strategic change for both KiwiSaver and Super

56
00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:56.320
together.

57
00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:00.280
Both are essential mechanisms that work together.

58
00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:02.480
So I leave you with this thought.

59
00:03:02.480 --> 00:03:06.680
This committee, itself a cross-party mechanism,

60
00:03:06.680 --> 00:03:10.280
has an opportunity to support that key recommendation,

61
00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:13.360
to promote a measured cross-party approach

62
00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:16.840
to considering long-term system change.

63
00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:19.240
This committee could review the mechanism

64
00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:21.560
suggested by the Commission and our report

65
00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:23.760
and doubtless improve it.

66
00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:25.960
We know collaboration is possible.

67
00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:27.920
The system will fail New Zealanders

68
00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:30.840
if we can't find new ways to think long-term,

69
00:03:30.840 --> 00:03:34.879
as New Zealand grapples with increasingly complex issues.

70
00:03:34.879 --> 00:03:38.800
Ngorera, te ina koutou, te ina koutou, te ina koutou, kato.

71
00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:39.560
Thank you so much.

72
00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:41.800
First question from Dr Lawrence, you know.

73
00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:42.760
Thank you, Chair.

74
00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:45.200
And I just want to first say thank you so much

75
00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:46.560
for all of your work, Jane.

76
00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:48.680
And I particularly appreciate your briefing

77
00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:50.400
on aging population and the flassie

78
00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:52.599
and social services and communities as well.

79
00:03:52.599 --> 00:03:55.520
My first question, so it's focused on one part of that,

80
00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:57.159
which is retirement village.

81
00:03:57.159 --> 00:03:58.800
Now we know we have seen the cabinet paper

82
00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:00.040
when it comes to retirement village

83
00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:03.520
and you mentioned your report that you were involved in that.

84
00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:06.439
In terms of the actual cabinet paper that we've seen

85
00:04:06.439 --> 00:04:10.800
and what you've heard from retirement village residents,

86
00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:13.280
do you think that the recommendation

87
00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:15.200
and the perspective has been reflected

88
00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:16.199
in that cabinet paper?

89
00:04:17.199 --> 00:04:22.399
The proposed legislation moves a long way ahead

90
00:04:22.399 --> 00:04:24.479
from where we were in 2020.

91
00:04:24.479 --> 00:04:27.360
Some of the changes have already been implemented

92
00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:29.519
by the operators, which is amazing.

93
00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:34.319
Some of the changes are yet to be implemented are still good

94
00:04:34.319 --> 00:04:36.039
and there are still a few areas

95
00:04:36.039 --> 00:04:38.000
that will continue to be the subject of debate,

96
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.079
which will be a very good and interesting select committee time.

97
00:04:42.079 --> 00:04:45.360
As part of the review, supplementary chair,

98
00:04:45.439 --> 00:04:49.600
what do you think would be the impact for retirees

99
00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:52.840
if retirement village doesn't look into capital sharing?

100
00:04:54.439 --> 00:04:57.840
That's probably the remaining number of the issues, right?

101
00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:02.840
And the real question then is when repayment might happen

102
00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:08.680
and how much repayment happens

103
00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:10.639
from the original capital sale, right?

104
00:05:10.639 --> 00:05:13.960
So those are really crunchy business debates

105
00:05:13.959 --> 00:05:15.759
and resident issues.

106
00:05:15.759 --> 00:05:18.359
And I think probably further the modelling needs

107
00:05:18.359 --> 00:05:22.279
to be done on this, but no matter what happens,

108
00:05:22.279 --> 00:05:24.560
the bill itself is a major advance

109
00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:25.919
on where we are at the moment,

110
00:05:25.919 --> 00:05:28.120
which is dealing with 20-year-old legislation.

111
00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:30.159
That's well out of date.

112
00:05:30.159 --> 00:05:32.799
Just to go to the chair, I have a new question on income.

113
00:05:32.799 --> 00:05:35.399
All right, so we'll come back to you later then.

114
00:05:35.399 --> 00:05:37.479
We have a supplementary problem in good leadership.

115
00:05:37.479 --> 00:05:39.199
Yeah, thank you for the work

116
00:05:39.199 --> 00:05:41.279
that you've done on this with HUD

117
00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:44.480
and noting that it appears

118
00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:48.440
that the capital repayments will be mandated to a year,

119
00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:50.400
which in my view and in my members' bill

120
00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:52.720
is not enough, minus three months.

121
00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:55.200
Lawrence Sunao and I did ask for an exposure draft

122
00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:57.280
of the bill and haven't received it.

123
00:05:57.280 --> 00:05:59.320
But I'm wondering, do you accept

124
00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:03.520
that exclusion of existing contracts

125
00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:07.720
will actually disadvantage those who are already

126
00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:08.720
in retirement villages,

127
00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:11.040
because they'll be the last cab off the rank

128
00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:13.840
to have the incentivisation for their licences

129
00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:16.280
to occupy to be sold by operators,

130
00:06:16.280 --> 00:06:18.200
particularly in an environment where we've got fast track

131
00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:21.439
building consent happening and expansion of villages.

132
00:06:21.439 --> 00:06:23.720
And if so, what actions would you like to see

133
00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:25.760
the government take around,

134
00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:28.640
rather than excluding retrospectivity,

135
00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:30.360
what further action could they take

136
00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:32.759
to fathom out a way that is fair

137
00:06:32.759 --> 00:06:35.560
to all retirement village residents

138
00:06:35.560 --> 00:06:38.879
so that we avoid a situation where those on current contracts

139
00:06:38.879 --> 00:06:42.560
will actually be disadvantaged by the new law?

140
00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:46.560
Yeah, again, I think this is the last crunchy hurdle

141
00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:48.120
to be jumped.

142
00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:51.159
You've got a longstanding legal principle

143
00:06:51.159 --> 00:06:54.240
that says contract, they just sort of changes

144
00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:58.079
aren't retrospective in most cases.

145
00:06:58.079 --> 00:07:01.360
You've got a good argument from the current residents going,

146
00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:03.000
yes, I know, but.

147
00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:04.920
And I think what will need to happen

148
00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:08.040
is some really good legal research on precedence.

149
00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:10.720
If there is a precedent for retrospectivity,

150
00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:11.480
what does it look like?

151
00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:12.720
Is it as strong as this one?

152
00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:13.920
I don't know.

153
00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:16.879
I don't know whether that work's been done by hand yet,

154
00:07:16.879 --> 00:07:18.520
but I can see that it's going to have to be

155
00:07:18.520 --> 00:07:19.840
to help resolve this issue.

156
00:07:19.840 --> 00:07:21.600
Just one more suffer, fine, yeah.

157
00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:24.920
And acknowledging that we had the Residential Tenancies Act,

158
00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:26.879
which could be considered an analogue,

159
00:07:26.879 --> 00:07:30.680
we've had changes made during COVID to commercial tenancies,

160
00:07:30.680 --> 00:07:32.520
which were retrospective in application

161
00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:35.280
and we've recently had statements in the House

162
00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:38.440
by Honourable Brock Van Velden that question the nature

163
00:07:38.440 --> 00:07:41.240
of particular provisions of contracts,

164
00:07:41.240 --> 00:07:43.080
saying that if they are just provisions,

165
00:07:43.080 --> 00:07:44.440
they may not be retrospective.

166
00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:46.920
So in all of that context, absolutely

167
00:07:46.920 --> 00:07:49.400
endorse what you've just said about further legal work.

168
00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:50.720
That's right.

169
00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:53.440
Again, every example that could be found

170
00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:57.080
for an equivalent approach would be helpful to that argument.

171
00:07:57.080 --> 00:07:57.760
Thank you.

172
00:07:57.760 --> 00:07:59.600
That's a commentary from Dr David Witsman.

173
00:07:59.600 --> 00:08:01.200
Yeah, a supplementary on this.

174
00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:02.520
Never talked about capital share,

175
00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:05.160
and we're talking about timing really, aren't we?

176
00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:09.160
Has there been any international comparative analysis

177
00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:12.760
of where our sector sits as proposed to others?

178
00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:13.720
More opposed?

179
00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:18.280
The international comparators are not that simple, actually.

180
00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:20.080
Our side is quite different from others,

181
00:08:20.080 --> 00:08:23.840
which is no great surprise to anything in New Zealand, really.

182
00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:26.200
I've forgotten what the Australian situation is.

183
00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:26.879
Do you remember?

184
00:08:26.879 --> 00:08:28.000
Six minutes.

185
00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.560
Yeah, I think it is, but it varies at state and federal.

186
00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:33.879
But again, it's a very different coverage of license

187
00:08:33.879 --> 00:08:35.799
to occupy this as quite different.

188
00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:36.639
Yeah.

189
00:08:36.639 --> 00:08:39.439
So my instinctive response is always

190
00:08:39.439 --> 00:08:41.360
to find the answers to bring that home.

191
00:08:41.360 --> 00:08:43.840
But we caught up, which is why we had to go.

192
00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:47.840
To identify what the problem was here.

193
00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:48.360
All right.

194
00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:50.159
New question from Dr Vanessa.

195
00:08:50.159 --> 00:08:50.919
Thank you, manager.

196
00:08:50.919 --> 00:08:53.360
And thank you very much for all the contribution

197
00:08:53.360 --> 00:08:56.279
that you've made over the time as commissioner.

198
00:08:56.279 --> 00:09:00.559
It's been wonderful to watch and see from this committee

199
00:09:00.559 --> 00:09:03.360
how it's progressing.

200
00:09:03.399 --> 00:09:07.399
Previously, you've had reports around retirement age

201
00:09:07.399 --> 00:09:12.399
and basically recommended that the retirement age not

202
00:09:12.399 --> 00:09:15.399
be adjusted or lifted.

203
00:09:15.399 --> 00:09:18.600
One of the things that we have to struggle with as a country

204
00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:27.720
is how we pay for our superannuation scheme going forward.

205
00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:30.920
If that's not the solution, what in your view

206
00:09:30.959 --> 00:09:35.519
could be a solution for the sustainability and ability

207
00:09:35.519 --> 00:09:39.839
of our superannuation scheme going forward?

208
00:09:39.839 --> 00:09:41.120
That's a really good question.

209
00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:43.679
And it is one of the core questions around the system

210
00:09:43.679 --> 00:09:48.439
itself, which is why we say tinkering or one-step solutions

211
00:09:48.439 --> 00:09:51.279
are not the way to deal with this, right?

212
00:09:51.279 --> 00:09:57.639
If we can get commitment to developing a long-term plan,

213
00:09:57.639 --> 00:10:00.519
then at that stage, all those competing tensions

214
00:10:00.519 --> 00:10:03.840
can be evaluated cross-portfolio, cross-party,

215
00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:07.399
and then where will we want to land as a country?

216
00:10:07.399 --> 00:10:10.759
It really needs to focus at a higher level on vision.

217
00:10:10.759 --> 00:10:13.879
What kind of country do we want for older New Zealanders

218
00:10:13.879 --> 00:10:16.079
and then work down from that?

219
00:10:16.079 --> 00:10:18.679
Affordability is absolutely a question.

220
00:10:18.679 --> 00:10:21.960
The answer is, are there other elements of government spending

221
00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:23.840
that could stop to help make it affordable,

222
00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:26.120
or is a good question?

223
00:10:26.120 --> 00:10:29.439
There are other mechanisms and system settings

224
00:10:29.440 --> 00:10:30.600
that could be looked at as well.

225
00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:33.760
For instance, means testing between 65 and 70,

226
00:10:33.760 --> 00:10:35.320
something like that.

227
00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:37.880
But none of these things should be considered an isolation

228
00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:40.080
without having a bit of an overall game plan.

229
00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:43.240
If we want to change things, then can we do it

230
00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:45.480
in a meaningful and holistic way

231
00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:47.680
that gets the best set of results

232
00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:51.120
for what is a series of quite complicated problems?

233
00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:53.520
Just a supplementary on that.

234
00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:56.960
What work have you done so far in that area,

235
00:10:56.960 --> 00:11:01.040
or is there any recommendation for further research

236
00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:04.519
or public engagement that you would make?

237
00:11:04.519 --> 00:11:08.080
The recommendation is to develop a plan.

238
00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:12.000
It's a very large document, and it's excellent bedtime reading.

239
00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:13.720
Yeah.

240
00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:15.759
All right, I support you, Trom.

241
00:11:15.759 --> 00:11:19.400
Yeah, thank you, Commissioner.

242
00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:23.000
I'm really concerned about a particular cohort of New Zealanders

243
00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.960
who don't fall into the traditional thing

244
00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:29.080
we've relied on around home ownership and KiwiSaver funds.

245
00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:31.960
And when I look at our current superannuation,

246
00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:35.480
it feels to me like an efficient universal basic income

247
00:11:35.480 --> 00:11:39.000
at an end of life where targeting would be inefficient.

248
00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.280
What is your concern for that cohort

249
00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:44.240
who are now couch surfing or even homeless

250
00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:47.080
if we were to continue with incremental change

251
00:11:47.080 --> 00:11:51.879
or just changing settings rather than comprehensive reform?

252
00:11:51.879 --> 00:11:53.639
It's, again, another good question.

253
00:11:53.639 --> 00:11:56.360
This is almost a forgotten cohort,

254
00:11:56.360 --> 00:11:59.199
which is why we keep saying we cannot do

255
00:11:59.199 --> 00:12:01.439
individual system change in isolation.

256
00:12:01.439 --> 00:12:03.279
So if you are of the view, for instance,

257
00:12:03.279 --> 00:12:07.919
that if you just put NZ Super age up, end of problem, job done,

258
00:12:07.919 --> 00:12:10.720
that's the narrowest of narrow views

259
00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:16.159
and does not take into account the impacts on a series

260
00:12:16.159 --> 00:12:18.399
of different types of people.

261
00:12:18.399 --> 00:12:21.240
Those impacts need to be analysed carefully.

262
00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:24.200
So those people that you're talking about now,

263
00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:27.480
we are predicting that this is going to rise considerably.

264
00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:32.759
